In [[divination]], an '''anachitis''', or '''anancitis''',<ref name=rulandus>{{cite book |title=A Lexicon of Alchemy or Alchemical Dictionary |last=Rulandus |first=Martin the Elder |year=1612 |location=Frankfurt }}</ref> meaning "stone of necessity"<ref>{{cite book |title=Three Books of Occult Philosophy |last=Agrippa |first=Heinrich Cornelius |editor=Tyson, Donald |others=Freake, James (tr.) |origyear=1531 |year=1993 |publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide |isbn=0-87542-832-0 |page=42 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5YjXnoAaYowC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=anancitis+-wikipedia}}</ref> is a stone used to call up [[spirit]]s from water.<ref>{{cite book |title=Encyclopædia metropolitana; or, System of universal knowledge |last=Smedley |first=Edward | authorlink=Edward Smedley|author2=Taylor, W. Cooke|author3= Thompson, Henry|author4= Rich, Elihu |year=1855 |publisher=Richard Griffin |location=London and Glasgow |page=350 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=afsIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA350&dq=Anachitis }}</ref> It was described as a type of [[diamond]] by [[Martin Ruland the Elder]].<ref name=rulandus/>

The stone was used in [[classical antiquity]] by the [[Magi]], being described by [[Pliny the Elder]] as one of their "dreadful lies".<ref>{{cite book |title=Ancient Natural History: Histories of Nature |last=French |first=Roger |year=1994 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=0-415-08880-1 |page=227 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I6ztfXbCaacC&pg=PT253&lpg=PT253&dq=anancitis+-wikipedia#PPT253,M1 }}</ref> Its use had fallen out of favour by the [[Middle Ages]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Magical Jewels of the Middle Ages and the Renaissance Particularly in England |last=Evans |first=Joan |year=2004 |publisher=Kessinger Publishing |isbn=0-7661-8224-X |page=31 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=okwTgGEIorMC&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=anancitis+-wikipedia}}</ref>

