{{Politics of Guyana}}

The '''Guiana United Muslim Party''' (GUMP) was a political party in [[Guyana]].

==History==
The party was set up in 1964 with assistance from the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] and the British authorities, and was led by Hoosein Ganie.<ref name=SGR>Stephen G Rabe (2006) ''U.S. Intervention in British Guiana: A Cold War Story'', Univ of North Carolina Press, p130</ref><ref>[http://www.stabroeknews.com/2009/guyana-review/05/28/the-indian-presence-in-guyana/ The Indian presence in Guyana] Stabroek News, 28 May 2009</ref> The American and British governments hoped the new party, together with the [[Justice Party (Guyana)|Justice Party]] (which the CIA was also funding), would take votes from the [[People's Progressive Party (Guyana)|People's Progressive Party]] (PPP), whose left-wing leanings they were concerned about.<ref>[http://www.guyana.org/features/guyanastory/chapter174.html The 1964 election campaign] Guyana.org</ref> Although the CIA estimated that the Justice Party and GUMP could win three seats in the  [[British Guiana general election, 1964|1964 general elections]],<ref name=SGR/> neither did; GUMP received only 0.5% of the vote and failed to win a seat,<ref name=N1>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume I'', pp366-368 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928357-6}}</ref> whilst the PPP emerged as the largest party, but was unable to form a government.

In the [[Guyanese general election, 1968|1968 elections]] it received only 0.3% of the vote and again failed to win a seat. The party did not contest any further elections.<ref>Nohlen, p365</ref>

