{{Infobox Jewish leader | honorific-prefix = | name = Joseph Saragossi | honorific-suffix = | title = | image = קבר רבי יוסי סרגוסי2.JPG | caption = Tomb of Saragossi, [[Ein Zeitim]], [[Israel]]. According to legend a Jewish community was saved after praying at this tomb. The ruler of the time was demanding 500 white cocks.<ref name=vilnay>{{cite book|last=Vilnay|first=Zev|title=Legends of Palestine p. 383|year=2003|pages=512|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VkA6-0-aDdIC&dq=%22joseph+Saragossi%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> | synagogue = | synagogueposition = | yeshiva = | yeshivaposition = | organisation = | organisationposition = | began = | ended = | predecessor = | successor = | rabbi = | rebbe = | kohan = | hazzan = | rank = | other_post = <!---------- Personal details ----------> | birth_name = | birth_date = 1460 | birth_place = | death_date = 1507 | death_place = | yahrtzeit = | buried = | nationality = | denomination = | residence = | dynasty = | parents = | father = | mother = | spouse = | children = | occupation = | profession = | alma_mater = | semicha = | signature = }} {{Yishuv haYashan}} '''Joseph Saragossi''', ({{lang-he|'''יוסף סרגוסי'''}}) (1460 – 1507) was a Spanish-born [[rabbi]] and [[kabbalist]] of the 15th and 16th centuries. He is credited with developing [[Safed]] into an important [[Jewish]] and [[Kabbalah|kabbalistic]] centre.<ref>{{harvnb|Fern Andrews|1976|p=145}}</ref> Due to a legend he is known as ''Tzaddik ha-Lavan'' (White Saint) or ''Tzaddik ha-Tarnegolim'' (Cockerel Saint.)
==Biography== Although Saragossi was born in 15th-century Spain, it is possible that his family did not originate in the Spanish town of [[Saragossa]], as his name implies, but rather Zaragoza ([[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]]) in [[Sicily]].<ref>{{harvnb|Adler|Schechter|Neuman|1956|p=332}}. Although he has been called "the Sefardi", which indicates Spanish extraction, this may only be a generic term for the exiles of 1492.</ref> He was banished with the rest of the Jewish community in 1492 and travelled through Sicily to [[Beirut]] and [[Sidon]]. He settled in Safed, where he became a rabbi.<ref name=JE>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/13193-saragossi-joseph Joseph Saragossi] ''Jewish Encyclopedia''.</ref> There were about 300 Jews there who had originally come from the [[Berber people|Berbers]], [[Sephardim]] and [[Moriscos]], but they had no natural leader.<ref name=graetz/>
Saragossi became a rabbi and a leader of the Jewish people despite his quiet manner. His charismatic personality was used to foster the growth of peace and harmony within the community. He endeavored to show reconciliation and mutual respect towards Safed's Muslim and Arab inhabitants.<ref name=graetz/> Saragossi's influence in Safed has been compared to the Italian [[Obadiah ben Abraham Bartenura|Obadyah di Bertinoro]] who made a similar contribution to the community in Jerusalem.<ref name=graetz>{{cite book|last=Graetz|first=Heinrich|title=History of the Jews, Vol. IV (in Six Volumes): From the Rise of the Kabbala p.399|year=2009|page=399|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dfK5t5TJnoUC&dq=%22joseph+Saragossi%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
When Saragossi indicated his intention to leave Safed, the people of Safed persuaded him to remain, offering to pay him an annual retainer. The respect of the Arab community was demonstrated when their Muslim governor promised to provide 33 of the 50 [[ducat]]s that was offered to Saragossi as an annual payment.<ref name=JE/><ref name=graetz/> Combining Talmudic with kabbalistic knowledge, Saragossi created a movement interested in Kabbalistic Jewish study in Safed.<ref name=graetz/> His kabbalistic teachings attracted the attention of [[David ben Solomon ibn Abi Zimra|David ibn Abu Zimra]].<ref name=JE/>
In accordance with his wish, Saragossi was buried adjacent to the tomb of [[Judah bar Ilai]], the site where he experienced a revelation of the prophet [[Elijah]].<ref name="Vilnay 2003 383">{{harvnb|Vilnay|2003|p=383}}</ref> The object of a legend in which a salvation was wrought at his graveside involving the procurement of 500 pure white chickens, he was thereafter called the ''Tzaddik ha-Lavan'' (White Saint) or the ''Tzaddik ha-Tarnegolim'' (Cockrel Saint.)<ref name="Vilnay 2003 383"/> At the turn of the 19th-century, Saragossi's tomb at [[Ein Zeitim|'Ain Zaitun]] was the object of a weekly pilgrimage from the morning after Passover (22nd [[Nisan]]) until the 18th [[Iyyar]].<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12149-pilgrimage Pilgrimage], ''Jewish Encyclopedia''.</ref>
