{{Other people|Peter Gilmore|Peter Gilmore (disambiguation)}} {{BLP sources|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox religious biography | name = Peter Howard Gilmore | image = Peter H Gilmore 2 by David Shankbone.jpg | image_size = | caption = Gilmore in October 2007 | birth_name = Peter Howard Gilmore | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|5|24}} | birth_place = [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]] | death_date = | death_place = | profession = Author, musician, [[occultist]], [[Priest]] | known_for = [[The Satanic Scriptures]] | spouse_type = | spouse = [[Peggy Nadramia]] | children = | signature = | religion = [[Satanism]] | denomination = [[Church of Satan]] | title = [[wiktionary:High Priest|High Priest]]; [[Magus]] | honorific_prefix = [[His Eminence]] }} {{LaVeyan Satanism box}}
'''Peter Howard Gilmore''' (born May 24, 1958) is an American composer, artist, and author. He is the [[high priest]] of the [[Church of Satan]]{{sfn|Open Questions: Diverse Thinkers Discuss God, Religion, and Faith|Luís F. Rodrigues|2010|p=125}} and author of ''[[The Satanic Scriptures]]''.{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|2010|page=93}} Gilmore graduated from [[NYU]] with both a [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor's]] and [[master's degree]] in music composition.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
He was appointed [[wiktionary:High Priest|High Priest]] of the Church in 2001 by Magistra [[Blanche Barton]]. As a representative of the Church of Satan, Gilmore has been interviewed on numerous [[television]] and [[radio]] programs dealing with the topic of [[Satanism]], including appearances on [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History]], the [[BBC]], [[Syfy]], ''[[Point of Inquiry]]'', and [[Bob Larson]]'s [[Christian]] radio show.{{sfn|Open Questions: Diverse Thinkers Discuss God, Religion, and Faith|Luís F. Rodrigues|2010|page=125}}
==Biography== {{Wikinews|Satanism: An interview with Church of Satan High Priest Peter Gilmore}} Gilmore was raised in [[upstate New York]]. He visited [[New York City]] regularly throughout his youth and moved to [[Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan|Hell's Kitchen]] in 1980. He read ''[[The Satanic Bible]]'' at age thirteen and has described [[The Church of Satan]] as "the motivating philosophical force in my life" ever since.{{sfn|Open Questions: Diverse Thinkers Discuss God, Religion, and Faith|Luís F. Rodrigues|2010|page=125}}
In 1989, he and his wife [[Peggy Nadramia]] began publishing a Satanic journal, ''[[The Black Flame (magazine)|The Black Flame]]'', and continues to publish issues sporadically. In 2005, Gilmore wrote the new introduction to [[Anton LaVey]]'s ''[[The Satanic Bible]]'', and his essay on Satanism was published in ''The Encyclopedia of Religion and Nature''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i4mvAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Encyclopedia+of+Religion+and+Nature&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIz6qVm-ngyAIVT_FjCh0M6gG6#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Religion and Nature|work=google.com}}</ref>
===The Satanic Scriptures=== In [[Walpurgis Night]] 2007, a hard cover edition of ''[[The Satanic Scriptures]]'', a book that collects his essays and other writings was released. On October 13, 2007, a paperback ({{ISBN|0976403595}}) was released. The book includes rituals that were previously not public, such as marriages and Satanic burials.
In Walpurgis Night of 2012, it was announced that an edition in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] was in production to be released on Halloween.
===Essays=== A large part of the essays were released before the book, however, some of the essays included in the book are improved variations. Some, including the essay published in the extract, deal with what the Church of Satan considers pseudo-Satanists, and those who refuse to join the Church, forming their own groups. Magus Gilmore is not too critical of the legitimate Satanists who never join the Church itself, yet disdainfully denounces heretical devil-worshiping [[Christianism|Christians]] who foolishly [[Animal sacrifice|sacrifice animals]] and worship a legendary and anti-theistic God.
Other essays touch on the similarity between [[Fascism|fascist aesthetics]] and Satanism, along with a multitude of political issues that correlate with the Satanic point of view, as the Index released demonstrates. It includes, but is not limited to, issues such as terrorism in the United States, [[Gay rights|gay rights]], and much more.
===Rituals=== Many of the rituals detailed in the book were previously only known to members of the priesthood in the Church of Satan, as the wedding rite that was carried out by the founder Anton LaVey, along with the details of a Satanic funeral, is supposed which is a variation of which was made for him.
